DO’s of Social Media
1) Think Before Posting
Always take a moment to think before sharing anything online. Ask yourself whether the content is appropriate, truthful, and respectful. Once something is posted, it can be difficult to remove completely.

2) Use Respectful Language
Communicate politely and respectfully with others. Use kind words, maintain good manners, and avoid hurting anyone’s feelings. Positive communication creates a healthy online environment.

3) Maintain Your Privacy
Protect your personal information such as phone number, home address, passwords, bank details, and private photos. Use privacy settings wisely to control who can see your posts.

4) Verify Information Before Sharing
Before forwarding news, facts, or updates, always confirm whether the information is true and comes from a reliable source. This helps prevent the spread of misinformation.

5) Maintain a Professional Image
Your social media profile reflects your personality and can influence how teachers, employers, or others view you. Share meaningful, positive, and professional content that builds a good reputation.

6) Be Positive and Supportive
Encourage others, appreciate good work, and spread positivity. Social media should be used to inspire and support people rather than bring them down.

7) Use Strong Passwords
Keep your accounts secure by using strong passwords and enabling two-factor authentication whenever possible.

DON’Ts of Social Media
1) Do Not Post Offensive Content

Avoid posting abusive, hateful, or inappropriate content that may hurt others or damage your image.

2) Do Not Spread Fake News
Never share unverified news, rumors, or misleading information. False information can create panic and harm people.

3) Do Not Over-Share Information
Do not reveal too much about your personal life, daily routine, location, or sensitive details online.

4) Do Not Fight Online
Avoid arguments, trolling, or engaging in negative conversations. Online fights can escalate quickly and leave a permanent record.

5) Do Not Post When Emotional
Never post when you are angry, upset, or emotional. Such posts may lead to regret later and can negatively affect relationships.

6) Do Not Trust Strangers Easily
Be cautious when interacting with unknown people online. Never share personal details with strangers.

7) Do Not Ignore Cyberbullying
Do not support or ignore cyberbullying. Report harmful behavior and stand against online harassment.
